OFFICIAL DESCRIPTION:

IMDB(Internet movie database):

IMDb (Internet Movie Database) is an online database of information related to films, television programs, home videos and video games, and internet streams, including cast, production crew and personnel biographies, plot summaries, trivia, and fan reviews and ratings. An additional fan feature, message boards, was abandoned in February 2017. Originally a fan-operated website, the database is owned and operated by IMDb.com, Inc., a subsidiary of Amazon.

As of October 2018, IMDb has approximately 5.3 million titles (including episodes) and 9.3 million personalities in its database, as well as 83 million registered users.

SOURCE: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IMDb

IMDB OFFCIAL LINK: https://www.imdb.com/

ROTTEN TOMATOES:

Rotten Tomatoes and the TomatometerT rating is the most trusted measurement of quality entertainment. As the leading online aggregator of movie and TV show reviews from professional critics, Rotten Tomatoes offers the most comprehensive guide to whats fresh. The world famous TomatometerT rating represents the percentage of positive professional reviews for films and TV shows and is used by millions every day, to help with their entertainment viewing decisions.

The Tomatometer score represents the percentage of professional critic reviews that are positive for a given film or television show. A Tomatometer score is calculated for a movie or TV show after it receives at least five reviews:

  1. When at least 60% of reviews for a movie or TV show are positive, a red tomato is displayed to indicate its Fresh status.

  2. When less than 60% of reviews for a movie or TV show are positive, a green splat is displayed to indicate its Rotten status.

ROTTEN TOMATOES OFFICIAL LINK: https://www.rottentomatoes.com/

OSCARS:

The Academy Awards, also known as the Oscars, are a set of awards for artistic and technical merit in the film industry, given annually by the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences (AMPAS), to recognize excellence in cinematic achievements as assessed by the Academys voting membership. The various category winners are awarded a copy of a golden statuette, officially called the Academy Award of Merit, although more commonly referred to by its nickname Oscar. The Academy Awards ceremony was first broadcast on radio in 1930 and televised for the first time in 1953. It is the oldest worldwide entertainment awards ceremony and is now seen live worldwide.A total of 3,072 Oscar statuettes have been awarded from the inception of the award through the 90th ceremony.

SOURCE: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Academy_Awards

ACADEMY AWARDS OFFICIAL LINK: https://oscar.go.com/

CAUSALITY/GENERIZABILITY:

The data set:movies.Rdata contains information(32 variables) about 651 movies with each row of the dataset representing an individual maovie and each column representing the descriptive variable regarding the movie, eg:release date, genre, runtime, etc. The dataset is a collection of movies from 1970 to 2014 and since the total number of movies produced in that time is 9962( according to imdb sources) the sample size(651) is less than 10% of the total population of movies and thus can be considered random sampling. Since the dataset is an observational study, any strong assosiation among variables can only be considered as correlations and not as causations.

Part 2: Research question

RQ: When the production house receives the final cut of a movie to be distribution in theatres, can it decide the box office performance of the movie based only on the characteristics of the movie ? : genre,cast,movie type, rating

Since I am assuming the movie has not yet released when it comes to the production house for distribution, variables such as release date, DVD sales, critics and audience ratings would not be there. Therefore I have not taken such variables into consideration during my data analysis.

I am interested in the research question in order develop a rough predictor of box office performance based on the movie characteristics which could help production companies in deciding which movies to select for theatre distribution as well as to aid individuals in their movie consumption choices.

Part 3: Exploratory data analysis

g0<-ggplot(data, aes(imdb_rating))+geom_density(size=1)+labs(title="Distribution of imdb ratings")

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.

boxplot(imdb_rating~top200_box,data=data,main="IMDB RATING VS BOX OFFICE",ylab = "imdb rating")

The imdb rating distriution is left skewed with most of the values lying between 6 to 8 rating.By seeing the boxplot of imdb rating and box office performance, we notice that the imdb ratings of movies in the top 200 box office are slightly higher than those which did not manage to reach the top 200. Hence to prove an assoisation between imdb ratings and BO performance we can do an inference test. Proving the hypothesis:( Ha IMD RATING(top_200_BO) > IMDB RATING(BO) ) could be useful as we can treat imdb rating as a precitor for box office success and use it further in our regression analysis since imdb_rating is a numerical variable(easier to use) as compared to top_200 which is a categorical variable.

#Checking imdb_score as proxy for box office performance
inference(y = imdb_rating, x =top200_box, data =data, statistic = "mean", type = "ht", null = 0, alternative = "less", method = "theoretical")
## Response variable: numerical
## Explanatory variable: categorical (2 levels) 
## n_no = 636, y_bar_no = 6.4778, s_no = 1.088
## n_yes = 15, y_bar_yes = 7.14, s_yes = 0.6916
## H0: mu_no =  mu_yes
## HA: mu_no < mu_yes
## t = -3.6046, df = 14
## p_value = 0.0014

Th inference test for hypothesis:Ha IMD RATING(top_200_BO) > IMDB RATING(BO) has generated a significant p value(0.0014) which means we can treat the variable: imdb_rating as a significant predictor for box office success. We will use this conclusion in the remiander of the data analysis.

Part 4: Modeling

I have used the following variables:title_type,genre,mpaa_rating,best_actor_win,best_actress_win,best_dir_win to predict the future imdb_rating of movies. I have excluded the other variable from regression analysis since those details regarding the movie(DVD info, critics,audience rating,oscar win/nomination for movie) would not be avaialble before the movie released.Thus I have selected only those movies whose details will be available with the production house before the movies release. The future imdb_rating of the movie is assosiated to its box office success, proved earlier through inference testing.

#constructing multiple regression model:
model<-lm( imdb_rating ~ title_type + genre + mpaa_rating + best_actor_win + best_actress_win + best_dir_win, movies)
summary(model)

From the model variables:title_type, genre, best_dir_win, mpaa_rating seem to have high p-values whereas best_actor_win, best_actress_win do not seem to have significant p values. The overall significance level (2e-16) is high, however the adjusted R value is not vey high(0.2548) signifying the low predictive power of the model. This is so since all the variables ate categorical values. We must now utilize a model selction technique to determine which are the most significant predictors to keep to ensure a parsimonious model.

#Backward Elimination (p-values)

On using the backward elimination model selection, we have found that all the variables are included in this model. This means that the lower significance variables (best_actor_win, best_actress_win) when removed from the model reduce the adjusted R value which is not desirable.

#Model Check:

par(mfrow = c(2,2))
hist(model$residuals)
plot(model,which=1)
plot(model,which=2)

We have performed the following checking conditions required for any regression model:

  1. No relationship between predictors(x1,x2,x3,) and predicted variable(y): random scatter in residual plot
  2. Nearly normal residuals: histogram of residuals is nearly normal around 0 (slightly left skewed, can be managed by large size of dataset
  3. constant variability of residuals: as seen in the normal Q-Q plot
  4. independent residuals: 651 movies are a random sample of the entire population of movies(>10% sample) as seen by the various value distributions of the variables (pie charts)

The confidence interval of the priction for imdb_rating: [actual-1.87 , actual+1.87]

Part 6: Conclusion

We selected appropriate variables from the main dataset which would be accesible to the production houses before a films release. Based on those variables we created a prediction model for predicting the future box office success of the movies(based on its imdb rating). Since most of the variables were categorical, the R squared value was not very high casting doubts on the predictability of the model. However we tested the model with a movie from 2016,and the model ws able to predict its imdb rating with an impressive error of 0.03. In conclusion,even though there is an assosiation between box office rank and imdb rating, it is difficult to predict the popularity of a movie before it is released in theatres.

A better predictive model can be constructed by taking the following points into consideration:

  1. Include more descriptive variables regarding movie details. The given dataset is pretty skewed in relation to title_type with Feature films as a clear majority(>50%) and genre with drama (50%). The dataset:movies.RData contains only 32 variables out of which there are some ones which are not helpful for data analysis like: URLs of rotten tomatoes and IMDB.
  2. Create new features from existing features by converting categorical variables to numerical variables utilising some sort of weighing rules. The larger the number of numerial variables in the dataset, the better the prediction.
  3. Selecting predictors which are good causal variables for the predicted variable. This requires real world knowledge of the dataset( here it is movie industry ) to know which characteristics of individual movies are reponsible for its popularity/ box office success. Selecting models based on adjusted R sqaured or p-values does not ensure that the parsimonious model has good predictive power in all cases. The model may also fail when it encounters datasets with diiferent distributions of variables.
